english:
  title: Song of the Clear River
  author: Sung Kan
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The setting sun descends into the bend of the clear river,
    A fragment of broken clouds aflame with crimson fish-tail glow.
    The green mountains mirror themselves on glassy waters,
    While ten thousand leagues of waves spill out autumn's hue.

    At the ferry crossing, travelers grow few and far between,
    A lone fishing boat bobs gently on the misty deep.
    Beside the twisted rocks, an ancient gnarled tree stands,
    As crows descend to peck, startling the yellow ox to flight.

    Upon a lonely pavilion perched at river's edge,
    A scholar tosses his beard toward the dying light.
    White-haired fisherman stirs the luminous mist,
    While cormorants cast sidelong glances, uncertain and suspicious.

    Autumn wind sweeps across the water, blurring the river,
    Friends call to one another, lean upon each other's sight,
    Gazing together toward the autumn sky.
    White gulls vanish into the haze, beyond all trace—
    Until a pair of them dart into the reeds and take their flight.
  footnotes:
    - The 'fish-tail' (魚尾) refers to the shape of clouds at sunset, a classical poetic image.
    - The 'glassy waters' (琉璃滑) evoke the perfect, mirror-like surface of water reflecting the mountains.
    - The scholar (高人) likely represents the poet himself or an idealized figure of refinement contemplating nature.
    - Cormorants (鸕鷀) were traditionally used in East Asian fishing and appear here as observers of the scene, adding to the poem's contemplative atmosphere.
